Homework 2

In this homework, we wish to investigate Abouir, et al., (2022) to assess the validity of several claims. First of all, we need to select the observations for different analysis.

library(idar)
data(codex)

# Cmax
Cmax_men = codex$cmax[codex$gender == 1]
Cmax_women = codex$cmax[codex$gender == 0]
Cmax_obese = codex$cmax[codex$obese == 1]
Cmax_non_obese = codex$cmax[codex$obese == 0]

# Tmax
Tmax_men = codex$tmax[codex$gender == 1]
Tmax_women = codex$tmax[codex$gender == 0]
Tmax_obese = codex$tmax[codex$obese == 1]
Tmax_non_obese = codex$tmax[codex$obese == 0]

# AUC
AUC_men = codex$auc[codex$gender == 1]
AUC_women = codex$auc[codex$gender == 0]
AUC_obese = codex$auc[codex$obese == 1]
AUC_non_obese = codex$auc[codex$obese == 0]

Question 1: Difference between groups for \(C_{\max}\)

Lets have a look at the empirical distributions:

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
boxplot_w_points(Cmax_women, Cmax_men, names = c("Women", "Men"),
                 ylab = "Cmax (ng/ml)")
boxplot_w_points(Cmax_obese, Cmax_non_obese, names = c("Obese", "Non-obese"), ylab = "Cmax (ng/ml)")

Based on these graphs, it is reasonable to believe that some outliers are present. Thus, we select Wilcoxon test to compare the mean in different groups.

wilcox.test(Cmax_women, Cmax_men, alternative = "less")
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum exact test
## 
## data:  Cmax_women and Cmax_men
## W = 43, p-value = 0.001661
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is less than 0
wilcox.test(Cmax_obese, Cmax_non_obese, alternative = "less")
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum exact test
## 
## data:  Cmax_obese and Cmax_non_obese
## W = 85, p-value = 0.1335
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is less than 0

From the result we can see that the p-value = 0.001661 in the first test is smaller than 0.05, which indicates there are some evidence against the null hypotheses in favor of the alternative. Therefore, at the 95% confidence level, we reject the null and accept the alternative hypothesis that the mean of the variable cmax in group of women is less than that in men. However, for the second test, there isnt an evidence to reject the null hypotheses in which we assert that there is no obvious difference in cmax between group of obese and non_obese.

t.test(Cmax_women, Cmax_men, alternative = "less")
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Cmax_women and Cmax_men
## t = -2.9365, df = 19.255, p-value = 0.004194
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is less than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##       -Inf -42.53625
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  122.8219  226.1786
t.test(Cmax_obese, Cmax_non_obese, alternative = "less")
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Cmax_obese and Cmax_non_obese
## t = -1.7488, df = 21.493, p-value = 0.0473
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is less than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##       -Inf -1.107418
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  138.6667  203.4433

Comparing the result of t.test to wilcox.test, we can get the same conclusion for the first test. However the conclusion for second test is opposite. Actually, the p-value in the t-test is around 0.05, which is also an indication of double check.
